# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pharmacokinetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The drug travels by some route of administration (oral, topical-dermal, etc.) in a chosen dosage form (e.g., tablets, capsules, or in solution).
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Absorption by some other routes, such as intravenous therapy, intramuscular injection, enteral nutrition, is even more straightforward and there is less variability in absorption and bioavailability is often near 100%.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Intravascular administration does not involve absorption, and there is no loss of drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The fastest route of absorption is inhalation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Absorption is a primary focus in drug development and medicinal chemistry, since a drug must be absorbed before any medicinal effects can occur.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Moreover, the drug's pharmacokinetic profile can be easily and significantly changed by adjusting factors that affect absorption.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Oral ingestion is the most common route of administration of pharmaceuticals.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Passing through the esophagus to the stomach, the contents of the capsule or tablet are absorbed by the GI tract.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The absorbed pharmaceutical is then passed through the liver and kidneys.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The rate of dissolution is a key target for controlling the duration of a drug's effect, and as such, several dosage forms that contain the same active ingredient may be available, differing only in the rate of dissolution.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] If a drug is supplied in a form that is not readily dissolved, it may be released gradually and act for longer.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Having a longer duration of action may improve compliance since the medication will not have to be taken as often.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Additionally, slow-release dosage forms may maintain concentrations within an acceptable therapeutic range over a longer period, whereas quick-release dosage forms may have sharper peaks and troughs in serum concentration.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] As can be inferred from the Noyes–Whitney equation, the rate of dissolution may be modified primarily by altering the surface area of the solid by altering the particle size (e.g., with micronization).
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] For many drugs, reducing the particle size reduces the dose needed to achieve the same therapeutic effect.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The particle size reduction increases the specific surface area and the dissolution rate and does not affect solubility.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The rate of dissolution may also be altered by choosing a suitable polymorph of a compound.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Different polymorphs have different solubility and dissolution rate characteristics.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Specifically, crystalline forms dissolve slower than amorphous forms since they require more energy to leave the lattice during dissolution.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The stablest crystalline polymorph has the lowest dissolution rate.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Dissolution also differs between anhydrous and hydrous forms of a drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Anhydrous forms often dissolve faster but sometimes are less soluble.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Esterification is also used to control solubility.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] For example, stearate and estolate esters of drugs have decreased solubility in gastric fluid.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Later, esterases in the gastrointestinal tract (GIT) wall and blood hydrolyze these esters to release the parent drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Coatings on a tablet or pellet may act as barriers to reducing the dissolution rate.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Coatings may also be used to control where dissolution takes place.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] For example, enteric coatings only dissolve in the basic environment of the intestines.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Drugs held in solution do not need to be dissolved before being absorbed.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Lipid-soluble drugs are absorbed more rapidly than water-soluble drugs.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The gastrointestinal tract is lined with epithelial cells.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Drugs must pass through or permeate these cells to be absorbed into the bloodstream.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Cell membranes may act as barriers to some drugs.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] They are essentially lipid bilayers which form semipermeable membranes.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Pure lipid bilayers are generally permeable only to small, uncharged solutes.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Hence, whether or not a molecule is ionized will affect its absorption, since ionic molecules are charged.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Solubility favors charged species, and permeability favors neutral species.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Some molecules have special exchange proteins and channels to facilitate movement from the lumen into the circulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The fatty acid chains repel ionized, charged molecules.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] This means that the ionized molecules cannot pass through the intestinal membrane and be absorbed.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation offers a way to determine the proportion of a substance that is ionized at a given pH.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] In the stomach, drugs that are weak acids (such as aspirin) will be present mainly in their non-ionic form, and weak bases will be in their ionic form.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Since non-ionic species diffuse more readily through cell membranes, weak acids will have a higher absorption in the highly acidic stomach.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] However, the reverse is true in the basic environment of the intestines—weak bases (such as caffeine) will diffuse more readily since they will be non-ionic.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] This aspect of absorption has been targeted by medicinal chemists.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] For example, they may choose an analog that is more likely to be in a non-ionic form.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] Also, the chemists may develop prodrugs of a compound—these chemical variants may be more readily absorbed and then metabolized by the body into the active compound.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] However, changing the structure of a molecule is less predictable than altering dissolution properties, since changes in chemical structure may affect the pharmacodynamic properties of a drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/absorption-pharmacology] The solubility and permeability of a drug candidate are important physicochemical properties the scientist wants to know as early as possible.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] In pharmacology, **bioavailability** is a subcategory of absorption and is the fraction (%) of an administered drug that reaches the systemic circulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] By definition, when a medication is administered intravenously, its bioavailability is 100%.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] However, when a medication is administered via routes other than intravenous, its bioavailability is lower due to intestinal epithelium absorption and first-pass metabolism.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Thereby, mathematically, bioavailability equals the ratio of comparing the area under the plasma drug concentration curve versus time (AUC) for the extravascular formulation to the AUC for the intravascular formulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] AUC is used because AUC is proportional to the dose that has entered the systemic circulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Bioavailability of a drug is an average value; to take population variability into account, deviation range is shown as ±.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] To ensure that the drug taker who has poor absorption is dosed appropriately, the bottom value of the deviation range is employed to represent real bioavailability and to calculate the drug dose needed for the drug taker to achieve systemic concentrations similar to the intravenous formulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] To dose without knowing the drug taker's absorption rate, the bottom value of the deviation range is used in order to ensure the intended efficacy, unless the drug is associated with a narrow therapeutic window.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] For dietary supplements, herbs and other nutrients in which the route of administration is nearly always oral, bioavailability generally designates simply the quantity or fraction of the ingested dose that is absorbed.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Bioavailability is a term used to describe the percentage of an administered dose of a xenobiotic that reaches the systemic circulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] It is denoted by the letter *f* (or, if expressed in percent, by *F*).
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] In nutritional science, which covers the intake of nutrients and non-drug dietary ingredients, the concept of bioavailability lacks the well-defined standards associated with the pharmaceutical industry.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] The pharmacological definition cannot apply to these substances because utilization and absorption is a function of the nutritional status and physiological state of the subject, resulting in even greater differences from individual to individual (inter-individual variation).
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Therefore, bioavailability for dietary supplements can be defined as the proportion of the administered substance capable of being absorbed and available for use or storage.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] In both pharmacology and nutrition sciences, bioavailability is measured by calculating the area under curve (AUC) of the drug concentration time profile.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] It is the fraction of exposure to a drug (AUC) through non-intravenous administration compared with the corresponding intravenous administration of the same drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] The comparison must be dose normalized (e.g., account for different doses or varying weights of the subjects); consequently, the amount absorbed is corrected by dividing the corresponding dose administered.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] In pharmacology, in order to determine absolute bioavailability of a drug, a pharmacokinetic study must be done to obtain a *plasma drug concentration vs time* plot for the drug after both intravenous (iv) and extravascular (non-intravenous, i.e., oral) administration.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] The absolute bioavailability is the dose-corrected area under curve (*AUC*) non-intravenous divided by *AUC* intravenous.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] The formula for calculating the absolute bioavailability, *F*, of a drug administered orally (po) is given below (where *D* is dose administered).
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Therefore, a drug given by the intravenous route will have an absolute bioavailability of 100% (*f* = 1), whereas drugs given by other routes usually have an absolute bioavailability of *less* than one.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] If we compare the two different dosage forms having same active ingredients and compare the two drug bioavailability is called comparative bioavailability.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Although knowing the true extent of systemic absorption (referred to as absolute bioavailability) is clearly useful, in practice it is not determined as frequently as one may think.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] The reason for this is that its assessment requires an *intravenous reference*; that is, a route of administration that guarantees all of the administered drug reaches systemic circulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Such studies come at considerable cost, not least of which is the necessity to conduct preclinical toxicity tests to ensure adequate safety, as well as potential problems due to solubility limitations.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] The intravenous and oral concentrations can then be deconvoluted by virtue of their different isotopic constitution, and can thus be used to determine the oral and intravenous pharmacokinetics from the same dose administration.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] This technique eliminates pharmacokinetic issues with non-equivalent clearance as well as enabling the intravenous dose to be administered with a minimum of toxicology and formulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] The technique was first applied using stable-isotopes such as 13C and mass-spectrometry to distinguish the isotopes by mass difference.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] More recently, 14C labelled drugs are administered intravenously and accelerator mass spectrometry (AMS) used to measure the isotopically labelled drug along with mass spectrometry for the unlabelled drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] In all such cases, to conduct an absolute bioavailability study requires that the drug be given intravenously.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Intravenous administration of a developmental drug can provide valuable information on the fundamental pharmacokinetic parameters of volume of distribution (*V*) and clearance (*CL*).
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] In pharmacology, relative bioavailability measures the bioavailability (estimated as the *AUC*) of a formulation (A) of a certain drug when compared with another formulation (B) of the same drug, usually an established standard, or through administration via a different route.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] When the standard consists of intravenously administered drug, this is known as absolute bioavailability (see above).
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Relative bioavailability is one of the measures used to assess bioequivalence (*BE*) between two drug products.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] For FDA approval, a generic manufacturer must demonstrate that the 90% confidence interval for the ratio of the mean responses (usually of *AUC* and the maximum concentration, *C*max) of its product to that of the "brand name drug" is within the limits of 80% to 125%.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Where *AUC* refers to the concentration of the drug in the blood over time *t* = 0 to *t* = ∞, *C*max refers to the maximum concentration of the drug in the blood.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] When *T*max is given, it refers to the time it takes for a drug to reach *C*max.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] While the mechanisms by which a formulation affects bioavailability and bioequivalence have been extensively studied in drugs, formulation factors that influence bioavailability and bioequivalence in nutritional supplements are largely unknown.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] As a result, in nutritional sciences, relative bioavailability or bioequivalence is the most common measure of bioavailability, comparing the bioavailability of one formulation of the same dietary ingredient to another.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] The absolute bioavailability of a drug, when administered by an extravascular route, is usually less than one (i.e., *F*< 100%).
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Various physiological factors reduce the availability of drugs prior to their entry into the systemic circulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Whether a drug is taken with or without food will also affect absorption, other drugs taken concurrently may alter absorption and first-pass metabolism, intestinal motility alters the dissolution of the drug and may affect the degree of chemical degradation of the drug by intestinal microflora.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Disease states affecting liver metabolism or gastrointestinal function will also have an effect.
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] Each of these factors may vary from patient to patient (inter-individual variation), and indeed in the same patient over time (intra-individual variation).
[src:pharmacokinetics/bioavailability] In clinical trials, inter-individual variation is a critical measurement used to assess the bioavailability differences from patient to patient in order to ensure predictable dosing.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] In pharmacology, **clearance** ( $Cl_{\text{tot}}$ ) is a pharmacokinetic parameter representing the efficiency of drug elimination.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] This is the rate of elimination of a substance divided by its concentration.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] The parameter also indicates the theoretical volume of plasma from which a substance would be completely removed per unit time.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Usually, clearance is measured in L/h or mL/min.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Excretion, on the other hand, is a measurement of the amount of a substance removed from the body per unit time (e.g., mg/min, μg/min, etc.).
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] While clearance and excretion of a substance are related, they are not the same thing.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] The concept of clearance was described by Thomas Addis, a graduate of the University of Edinburgh Medical School.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Substances in the body can be cleared by various organs, including the kidneys, liver, lungs, etc.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Thus, total body clearance is equal to the sum clearance of the substance by each organ (e.g., renal clearance + hepatic clearance + pulmonary clearance = total body clearance).
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] For many drugs, however, clearance is solely a function of renal excretion.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] In these cases, clearance is almost synonymous with **renal clearance** or **renal plasma clearance**.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Each substance has a specific clearance that depends on how the substance is *handled* by the nephron.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Clearance is a function of 1) glomerular filtration, 2) secretion from the peritubular capillaries to the nephron, and 3) reabsorption from the nephron back to the peritubular capillaries.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Clearance is variable in zero-order kinetics because a constant amount of the drug is eliminated per unit time, but it is constant in first-order kinetics, because the amount of drug eliminated per unit time changes with the concentration of drug in the blood.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Clearance can refer to the volume of plasma from which the substance is removed (i.e., *cleared*) per unit time or, in some cases, inter-compartmental clearances can be discussed when referring to redistribution between body compartments such as plasma, muscle, and fat.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] The clearance of a substance is the volume of plasma that contains the same amount of the substance as has been removed from the plasma per unit time.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] When referring to the function of the kidney, clearance is considered to be the *amount of liquid filtered out of the blood that gets processed by the kidneys* or *the amount of blood cleaned per time* because it has the units of a volumetric flow rate [ volume per unit time ].
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Other factors include the mass transfer coefficient, dialysate flow and dialysate recirculation flow for hemodialysis, and the glomerular filtration rate and the tubular reabsorption rate, for the kidney.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] A physiologic interpretation of clearance (at steady-state) is that clearance is *a ratio of the mass generation and blood (or plasma) concentration*.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] From the above definitions it follows that ${\frac {dC}{dt}}$ is the first derivative of concentration with respect to time, i.e. the change in concentration with time.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Clearance of a substance is sometimes expressed as the inverse of the time constant that describes its removal rate from the body divided by its volume of distribution (or total body water).
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] In steady-state, it is defined as the mass generation rate of a substance (which equals the mass removal rate) divided by its concentration in the blood.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] There is an important relationship between clearance, elimination half-life and distribution volume.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] (note the usage of Cl and not Κ, not to confuse with $K_{\text{el}}$ ).
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] This means, for example, that an increase in total clearance results in a decrease in elimination rate half-life, provided distribution volume is constant.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] For substances that exhibit substantial plasma protein binding, clearance is generally dependent on the total concentration (free + protein-bound) and not the free concentration.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Most plasma substances have primarily their free concentrations regulated, which thus remains the same, so extensive protein binding increases total plasma concentration (free + protein-bound).
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] This decreases clearance compared to what would have been the case if the substance did not bind to protein.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] The above equation (**10b**) makes clear the relationship between mass removal and *clearance*.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] It states that (with a constant mass generation) the concentration and clearance vary inversely with one another.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] If applied to creatinine (i.e. creatinine clearance), it follows from the equation that if the serum creatinine doubles the clearance halves and that if the serum creatinine quadruples the clearance is quartered.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] When the substance "C" is creatinine, an endogenous chemical that is excreted only by filtration, the clearance is an approximation of the glomerular filtration rate.
[src:pharmacokinetics/clearance-pharmacology] Inulin clearance is less commonly used to precisely determine glomerular filtration rate.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] In pharmacology, the **elimination** or **excretion** of a drug is understood to be any one of a number of processes by which a drug is eliminated (that is, cleared and excreted) from an organism either in an unaltered form (unbound molecules) or modified as a metabolite.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] The kidney is the main excretory organ although others exist such as the liver, the skin, the lungs or glandular structures, such as the salivary glands and the lacrimal glands.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Drugs are excreted from the kidney by glomerular filtration and by active tubular secretion following the same steps and mechanisms as the products of intermediate metabolism.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Therefore, drugs that are filtered by the glomerulus are also subject to the process of passive tubular reabsorption.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Glomerular filtration will only remove those drugs or metabolites that are not bound to proteins present in blood plasma (free fraction) and many other types of drugs (such as the organic acids) are actively secreted.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] In the proximal and distal convoluted tubules, non-ionised acids and weak bases are reabsorbed both actively and passively.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Weak acids are excreted when the tubular fluid becomes too alkaline and this reduces passive reabsorption.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Poisoning treatments use this effect to increase elimination, by alkalizing the urine causing forced diuresis which promotes excretion of a weak acid, rather than it getting reabsorbed.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] As the acid is ionised, it cannot pass through the plasma membrane back into the blood stream and instead gets excreted with the urine.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Acidifying the urine has the same effect for weakly basic drugs.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] On other occasions drugs combine with bile juices and enter the intestines.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] In the intestines the drug will join with the unabsorbed fraction of the administered dose and be eliminated with the faeces or it may undergo a new process of absorption to eventually be eliminated by the kidney.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] The other elimination pathways are less important in the elimination of drugs, except in very specific cases, such as the respiratory tract for alcohol or anaesthetic gases.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] The case of mother's milk is of special importance.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] The liver and kidneys of newly born infants are relatively undeveloped and they are highly sensitive to a drug's toxic effects.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] For this reason it is important to know if a drug is likely to be eliminated from a woman's body if she is breast feeding in order to avoid this situation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Pharmacokinetics studies the manner and speed with which drugs and their metabolites are eliminated by the various excretory organs.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] This elimination will be proportional to the drug's plasmatic concentrations.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] In order to model these processes a working definition is required for some of the concepts related to excretion.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] The plasma half-life or *half life of elimination* is the time required to eliminate 50% of the absorbed dose of a drug from an organism.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Or put another way, the time that it takes for the plasma concentration to fall by half from its maximum levels.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] The difference in a drug's concentration in arterial blood (before it has circulated around the body) and venous blood (after it has passed through the body's organs) represents the amount of the drug that the body has eliminated or *cleared*.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Although clearance may also involve other organs than the kidney, it is almost synonymous with **renal clearance** or **renal plasma clearance**.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Clearance is therefore expressed as the plasma volume totally free of the drug per unit of time, and it is measured in units of volume per units of time.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Clearance can be determined on an overall, organism level («systemic clearance») or at an organ level (hepatic clearance, renal clearance etc.).
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Where: $CL_{o}$ is the organ's clearance rate, $C_{A}$ is the drug's plasma concentration in arterial blood, $C_{V}$ is the drug's plasma concentration in venous blood and Q an organ's blood flow.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Each organ will have its own specific clearance conditions, which will relate to its mode of action.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] As «hepatic clearance» is an active process it is therefore determined by factors that alter an organism's metabolism such as the number of functioning hepatocytes, this is the reason that liver failure has such clinical importance.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] The steady state or *stable concentration* is reached when the drug's supply to the blood plasma is the same as the rate of elimination from the plasma.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] It is necessary to calculate this concentration in order to decide the period between doses and the amount of drug supplied with each dose in prolonged treatments.
[src:pharmacokinetics/elimination-pharmacology] Other parameters of interest include a drug's bioavailability and the *apparent volume of distribution*.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] The effect is most associated with orally administered medications, but some drugs still undergo first-pass metabolism even when delivered via an alternate route (e.g., IV, IM, etc.).
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] During this metabolism, drug is lost during the process of absorption which is generally related to the liver and gut wall.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] The liver is the major site of first pass effect; however, it can also occur in the lungs, vasculature or other metabolically active tissues in the body.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Notable drugs that experience a significant first pass effect are buprenorphine, chlorpromazine, cimetidine, diazepam, ethanol (drinking alcohol), imipramine, insulin, lidocaine, midazolam, morphine, pethidine, propranolol, and tetrahydrocannabinol (THC).
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] First-pass metabolism is not to be confused with phase I metabolism, which is a separate process.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] First-pass metabolism may occur in the liver (for propranolol, lidocaine, clomethiazole, and nitroglycerin) or in the gut (for benzylpenicillin and insulin).
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] The four primary systems that affect the first pass effect of a drug are the enzymes of the gastrointestinal lumen, gastrointestinal wall enzymes, bacterial enzymes and hepatic enzymes.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] After a water-soluble drug is swallowed, it is absorbed by the digestive system and enters the hepatic portal system.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] It is carried through the portal vein into the liver before it reaches the rest of the body.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] The liver metabolizes many drugs, sometimes to such an extent that only a small amount of active drug emerges from the liver to the rest of the circulatory system.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] This *first pass* through the liver thus may greatly reduce the bioavailability of the drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] An example of a drug where first-pass metabolism is a complication and disadvantage is in the antiviral drug remdesivir.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Remdesivir cannot be administered orally because the entire dose would be trapped in the liver with little achieving systemic circulation or reaching target organs and cells (for example, cells infected with SARS-CoV-2).
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] For this reason, remdesivir is administered by IV infusion, bypassing the portal vein.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] However, significant hepatic extraction still occurs because of second pass metabolism, whereby a fraction of venous blood travels through the hepatic portal vein and hepatocytes.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] In drug design, drug candidates may have good druglikeness but fail on first-pass metabolism because it is biochemically selective.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Physiologically based pharmacokinetic models (PBPK) are used to predict first-pass metabolism, although they require compound-specific adjustments due to variability in intestinal mucosal permeability and other factors.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Enzyme expression also varies between individuals, which may influence the efficiency of first-pass metabolism and thus the bioavailability of the drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Cytochromes P450, especially CYP3A4, play a crucial role in first-pass metabolism, affecting the bioavailability of drugs.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Converting a drug into a prodrug can help avoid first-pass metabolism, thereby improving its bioavailability.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] In *in vitro* models, such as the use of microfluidic chips that simulate the gut and liver, allow first-pass metabolism to be studied more accurately, facilitating the development of drugs with better absorption profiles.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Alternative routes of administration, such as insufflation, rectal administration, intravenous, intramuscular, inhalational aerosol, transdermal, or sublingual, avoid or partially avoid the first pass effect because they allow drugs to be absorbed directly into the systemic circulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Drugs with high first pass effect typically have a considerably higher oral dose than sublingual or parenteral dose.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] There is marked individual variation in the oral dose due to differences in the extent of first-pass metabolism, frequently among several other factors.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Oral bioavailability of many vulnerable drugs appears to be increased in patients with compromised liver function.
[src:pharmacokinetics/first-pass-effect] Bioavailability is also increased if another drug competing for first-pass metabolism enzymes is given concurrently (e.g., propranolol and chlorpromazine).
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Some textbooks combine the first two phases as the drug is often administered in an active form, which means that there is no liberation phase.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Others include a phase that combines distribution, metabolism and excretion into a disposition phase.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Other authors include the drug's toxicological aspect in what is known as *ADME-Tox* or *ADMET*.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The two phases of metabolism and excretion can be grouped together under the title elimination.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The study of these distinct phases involves the use and manipulation of basic concepts in order to understand the process dynamics.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The following are the most commonly measured pharmacokinetic metrics: The units of the dose in the table are expressed in moles (mol) and molar (M).
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] To express the metrics of the table in units of mass, instead of amount of substance, simply replace 'mol' with 'g' and 'M' with 'g/L'.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Similarly, other units in the table may be expressed in units of an equivalent dimension by scaling.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] In pharmacokinetics, *steady state* refers to the situation where the overall intake of a drug is fairly in dynamic equilibrium with its elimination.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] In practice, it is generally considered that once regular dosing of a drug is started, steady state is reached after 3 to 5 times its half-life.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] In steady state and in linear pharmacokinetics, AUCτ=AUC∞.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Models have been developed to simplify conceptualization of the many processes that take place in the interaction between an organism and a chemical substance.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Pharmacokinetic modelling may be performed either by noncompartmental or compartmental methods.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Multi-compartment models provide the best approximations to reality; however, the complexity involved in adding parameters with that modelling approach means that *monocompartmental models* and above all *two compartmental models* are the most-frequently used.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The model outputs for a drug can be used in industry (for example, in calculating bioequivalence when designing generic drugs) or in the clinical application of pharmacokinetic concepts.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Clinical pharmacokinetics provides many performance guidelines for effective and efficient use of drugs for human-health professionals and in veterinary medicine.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Models generally take the form of mathematical formulas that have a corresponding graphical representation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] A variety of analysis techniques may be used to develop models, such as nonlinear regression or curve stripping.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Noncompartmental methods estimate PK parameters directly from a table of concentration-time measurements.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Noncompartmental methods are versatile in that they do not assume any specific model and generally produce accurate results acceptable for bioequivalence studies.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Total drug exposure is most often estimated by area under the curve (AUC) methods, with the trapezoidal rule (numerical integration) the most common method.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Due to the dependence on the length of *x* in the trapezoidal rule, the area estimation is highly dependent on the blood/plasma sampling schedule.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] That is, the closer time points are, the closer the trapezoids reflect the actual shape of the concentration-time curve.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The number of time points available in order to perform a successful NCA analysis should be enough to cover the absorption, distribution and elimination phase to accurately characterize the drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Beyond AUC exposure measures, parameters such as Cmax (maximum concentration), Tmax (time to maximum concentration), CL and Vd can also be reported using NCA methods.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Compartment models methods estimate the concentration-time graph by modeling it as a system of differential equations.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] These models are based on a consideration of an organism as a number of related *compartments*.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Both single compartment and multi-compartment models are in use.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] PK compartmental models are often similar to kinetic models used in other scientific disciplines such as chemical kinetics and thermodynamics.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The advantage of compartmental over noncompartmental analysis is the ability to modify parameters and to extrapolate to novel situations.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The disadvantage is the difficulty in developing and validating the proper model.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Although compartment models have the potential to realistically model the situation within an organism, models inevitably make simplifying assumptions and will not be applicable in all situations.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] However complicated and precise a model may be, it still does not truly represent reality despite the effort involved in obtaining various distribution values for a drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] This is because the concept of distribution volume is a relative concept that is not a true reflection of reality.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The choice of model therefore comes down to deciding which one offers the lowest margin of error for the drug involved.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The simplest PK compartmental model is the one-compartmental PK model.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] This models an organism as one homogenous compartment.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] This *monocompartmental model* presupposes that blood plasma concentrations of the drug are the only information needed to determine the drug's concentration in other fluids and tissues.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] For example, the concentration in other areas may be approximately related by known, constant factors to the blood plasma concentration.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] In this one-compartment model, the most common model of elimination is first order kinetics, where the elimination of the drug is directly proportional to the drug's concentration in the organism.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] This is often called *linear pharmacokinetics*, as the change in concentration over time can be expressed as a linear differential equation ${\textstyle {\frac {dC}{dt}}=-k_{\text{el}}C}$ .
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Assuming a single IV bolus dose resulting in a concentration $C_{\text{initial}}$ at time $t=0$ , the equation can be solved to give $C=C_{\text{initial}}\times e^{-k_{\text{el}}\times t}$ .
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Not all body tissues have the same blood supply, so the distribution of the drug will be slower in those tissues than in others with a better blood supply.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Furthermore, there are some tissues (such as the brain tissue) that present a real barrier to the distribution of drugs, which may be breached with greater or lesser ease depending on the drug's characteristics.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Other tissues, such as the brain, can occupy a variable position depending on a drug's ability to passively transport (high lipophilicity) and evade active efflux to cross the blood**–**brain barrier (BBB) that separates the organ from the blood supply.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Two-compartment models vary depending on which compartment elimination occurs in.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The most common situation is that elimination occurs in the central compartment as the liver and kidneys are organs with a good blood supply.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] However, in some situations, elimination occurs in the peripheral compartment or even in both compartments.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] This can mean that there are three possible variations in the two compartment model, which still do not cover all possibilities.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] In the real world, each tissue will have its own distribution characteristics and none of them will be strictly linear.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The two-compartment model may not be applicable in situations where some of the enzymes responsible for metabolizing the drug become saturated, or where an active elimination mechanism is present that is independent of the drug's plasma concentration.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] This represents the *multi-compartment model* with a number of curves that express complicated equations in order to obtain an overall curve.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] A number of computer programs have been developed to plot these equations.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The most complex PK models (called PBPK models) rely on the use of physiological information to ease development and validation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The graph for the non-linear relationship between the various factors is represented by a curve; the relationships between the factors can then be found by calculating the dimensions of different areas under the curve.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The models used in *non-linear pharmacokinetics* are largely based on Michaelis–Menten kinetics.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] It can therefore be seen that non-linearity can occur because of reasons that affect the entire pharmacokinetic sequence: absorption, distribution, metabolism and elimination.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] At a practical level, a drug's bioavailability can be defined as the proportion of the drug that reaches the systemic circulation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] From this perspective the intravenous administration of a drug provides the greatest possible bioavailability, and this method is considered to yield a bioavailability of 1 (or 100%).
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Bioavailability of other delivery methods is compared with that of intravenous injection (absolute bioavailability) or to a standard value related to other delivery methods in a particular study (relative bioavailability).
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Once a drug's bioavailability has been established it is possible to calculate the changes that need to be made to its dosage in order to reach the required blood plasma levels.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Bioavailability is, therefore, a mathematical factor for each individual drug that influences the administered dose.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] where *De* is the effective dose, *B* bioavailability and *Da* the administered dose.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] That is the 100 mg administered represents a blood plasma concentration of 80 mg that has the capacity to have a pharmaceutical effect.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] where $Va$ is the drug's rate of administration and $\tau$ is the rate at which the absorbed drug reaches the circulatory system.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] When two drugs have the same bioavailability, they are said to be biological equivalents or bioequivalents.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The concept of bioequivalence is important since it is currently used as a yardstick in the authorization of generic drugs in many countries.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Bioanalytical methods are necessary to construct a concentration-time profile.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Chemical techniques are employed to measure the concentration of drugs in biological matrix, most often plasma.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Proper bioanalytical methods should be selective and sensitive.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] For example, microscale thermophoresis can be used to quantify how the biological matrix/liquid affects the affinity of a drug to its target.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Pharmacokinetics is often studied using mass spectrometry because of the complex nature of the matrix (often plasma or urine) and the need for high sensitivity to observe concentrations after a low dose and a long time period.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The most common instrumentation used in this application is LC-MS with a triple quadrupole mass spectrometer.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Tandem mass spectrometry is usually employed for added specificity.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Standard curves and internal standards are used for quantitation of usually a single pharmaceutical in the samples.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The samples represent different time points as a pharmaceutical is administered and then metabolized or cleared from the body.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Blank samples taken before administration are important in determining background and ensuring data integrity with such complex sample matrices.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Much attention is paid to the linearity of the standard curve; however it is common to use curve fitting with more complex functions such as quadratics since the response of most mass spectrometers is not linear across large concentration ranges.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] There is currently considerable interest in the use of very high sensitivity mass spectrometry for microdosing studies, which are seen as a promising alternative to animal experimentation.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Recent studies show that Secondary electrospray ionization (SESI-MS) can be used in drug monitoring, presenting the advantage of avoiding animal sacrifice.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Clinical pharmacokinetics (arising from the clinical use of population pharmacokinetics) is the direct application to a therapeutic situation of knowledge regarding a drug's pharmacokinetics and the characteristics of a population that a patient belongs to (or can be ascribed to).
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] An example is the relaunch of the use of ciclosporin as an immunosuppressor to facilitate organ transplant.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The drug's therapeutic properties were initially demonstrated, but it was almost never used after it was found to cause nephrotoxicity in a number of patients.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] However, it was then realized that it was possible to individualize a patient's dose of ciclosporin by analyzing the patients plasmatic concentrations (pharmacokinetic monitoring).
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] This practice has allowed this drug to be used again and has facilitated a great number of organ transplants.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Clinical monitoring is usually carried out by determination of plasma concentrations as this data is usually the easiest to obtain and the most reliable.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Ecotoxicology is the branch of science that deals with the nature, effects, and interactions of substances that are harmful to the environment such as microplastics and other biosphere harmful substances.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] Ecotoxicology is studied in pharmacokinetics due to the substances responsible for harming the environment such as pesticides can get into the bodies of living organisms.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] The health effects of these chemicals is thus subject to research and safety trials by government or international agencies such as the EPA or WHO.
[src:pharmacokinetics/pharmacokinetics] How long these chemicals stay in the body, the lethal dose and other factors are the main focus of Ecotoxicology.
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] Roughly speaking, the $V_{D}$ , as a property of a drug, measures the degree to which it is distributed in body tissue rather than the blood plasma.
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] Drug properties which cause high $V_{D}$ include high lipid solubility (non-polarity), low rates of ionization, or low plasma protein binding capabilities.
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] Disease states which increase $V_{D}$ include kidney failure (due to fluid retention) and liver failure (due to altered body fluid and plasma protein binding).
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] Conversely, dehydration may decrease $V_{D}$ .
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] The initial volume of distribution describes blood concentrations prior to attaining the apparent volume of distribution and uses the same formula.
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] Suppose one administers an *amount of drug* D intravascularly, then measures the *drug concentration in blood* $C_{0}$ (assuming enough time has elapsed for the drug to distribute, but not enough time for elimination).
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] If the drug remains entirely intravascularly, $V_{D}$ will be identical to the blood volume $V_{blood}$ .
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] However, if a drug diffuses out of the intravascular space into the tissues or interstitium, the measured concentration will be lower-than-expected compared to a hypothetical intravascular-only drug.
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] Therefore, $V_{D}>V_{blood}$ , with a higher $V_{D}$ value corresponding to a greater tendency for the drug to exit the intravascular space.
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] One clinical utility is that the dose required D to achieve a target plasma concentration $C_{0}$ can be determined if the $V_{D}$ for that drug is known.
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] The $V_{D}$ is **not** a physiological value; it is more a reflection of how a drug will distribute throughout the body depending on several physicochemical properties such as solubility, charge, size, etc.
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] The unit for $V_{D}$ may be reported extensively in litres (for a patient of given weight), or intensively as litres-per-kilogram.
[src:pharmacokinetics/volume-of-distribution] For example, chloroquine has much greater affinity for body fat than blood, resulting in a $V_{D}\approx 250L/kg$ compared to $V_{blood}\approx 0.08L/kg$ .
